      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "What this means\n- Copper(II) has by far the broadest coverage: ~2,000 ligands and ~9,000 measurements, reflecting its rich aqueous coordination chemistry with O/N/S donors and extensive study across bioinorganic and analytical contexts.\n- Iron(III) shows moderate coverage but less than Cu(II); extensive hydrolysis and polymerization in water limit comparable ligand-stability datasets under controlled conditions.\n- Iron(II) and copper(I) have fewer entries: Fe(II) due to air‑sensitivity (Fe2+ → Fe3+), and Cu(I) due to instability in aerated water (tends to disproportionate), both reducing the number of clean aqueous measurements.",
